Why do organisms change over time? Are there rules that guide this change? D'Arcy Thompson said in 1917 that even now, scientists cannot describe simple organic forms with math. But now, math is used to study change in mollusk shells. Our study looks at how math and experiments can explain how and how much mollusks change. We used X-ray pictures of Prunum shells to find math for shell shapes. We used a program called CerioShell to make models of shell shapes. These models help us understand big changes in mollusk evolution. A shell is like a tube that turns 360 degrees. Whorls are these turns. The shell's biggest whorl is the last one. The tip of the shell is the apex, and the end is the base. The opening is called the aperture. Shells can be seen from different views. A method is shown for counting whorls. We look at the shell's shape over time and space. This helps us understand how mollusks make their shells. We can change math and see how the shell changes.

Indonesia's rate of baby and small child death has not changed much in ten years. Indonesia is doing good work with many goals, like water and sanitation, but child and mother health is not improving enough. We will discuss reasons for this and need to make health system stronger, not just fix small problems.
Indonesia has more births with skilled workers, 72%. But, these include traditional workers who cannot help with problems. This shows more work is needed. Diarrhea cases in children under five have also gone down, but postnatal care is not good. Cesarian-section rates are low, at 4%, and lower in rural areas. This shows unequal access to healthcare. The poorest people have more trouble getting healthcare services, likely due to costs.
To improve baby and mother health, we need to decide if Indonesia should fix specific problems or strengthen the whole health system. Program-specific approaches can work well, but can also cause problems. They can take money and workers away from other areas. They can also cause service duplication. We should think about these things before choosing what to do.

Victorian novels are known for their detailed descriptions and focus on the rich people of the time. Two examples from this period are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These novels have mystery and strange things, which are not usual in other Victorian novels. This helps to show the characters and their feelings better. They use mystery through dreams or dream-like states. In Oliver Twist, the dreams show Oliver's feelings and what is happening to him. When he remembers the shooting, he feels out of control and scared. He can't stop it. This shows that Oliver does not have power over his life. This part is from chapter 28. It also shows that Oliver is giving up hope, as if Fagin is breaking him. The shooting is like a dream. He can't control it. He is scared and powerless. This shows that Oliver does not have control over his life.

Two years ago, I worked in an after school program. I helped Elementary students with their schoolwork. I was good at English and reading. A teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. He had trouble reading. I thought something was wrong. He knew some letters, but not others. He spoke English well, but his mother only spoke Spanish. I tried to talk with her. I learned Adrian could read, but he didn't know the alphabet well. I hope he's doing better now.

I tell this story to show that language barriers exist in schools. Even a child who speaks English well might have trouble reading. We must find a solution. For Adrian, the answer was tutoring. But for many children, it's more complicated. We need many methods together. The dual language system helps children learn two languages. It makes them smarter. But it cannot fix the problem alone. We need teachers with special skills. Not all teachers can be bilingual. But we can have helpers who speak two languages.

From when we are young, most of us hear about something bigger than us. Some go to church or search inside for answers. Some believe what their parents teach. Some do not. We try to understand our spirituality. We look for light in the dark.

My father said his favorite bird was a cardinal. We sat on our porch, smoking. He looked at the rain, remembering. He was thin, his hair less. He stared, not looking at me. I felt alone, afraid. I hugged him, sat close. We watched the rain together.

My father died in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The treatment did not help much. I did not want to watch him die. I wanted to remember him alive. I curled up in bed for three days. No one called me.

The old "Gothic Novel" is a mix of old and new. Ian Watt says this in his book "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." People like and dislike the Gothic mode. It is called "terrible sublime." Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto" is the first Gothic novel. It uses old and new ideas. Walpole mixes old theater and new novel styles to create a new kind of story. The Gothic genre uses old medieval theater, architecture, and traditions. In the past, "Gothic" meant different things. It was not seen as modern. The mix of old Gothic and new novels is why Gothic stays interesting.

One big idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. Chivalry was a way to train knights in the past. Walpole uses this idea in "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry is important because it shows the ideal knight. The knight is brave, honorable, and skilled. Walpole sees a lack of these traits in society. He writes about this in his characters. One character, Frederic, has many chivalric traits. He is a prince. He has suffered great tragedy. He is soon to be a Gothic hero. Walpole was writing during a troubled time. He may not have seen goodness in people. His writing shows this.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from customer order to delivery. It includes six steps: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These steps help businesses provide good service to customers.
Production, the first step, starts the supply chain. Managers need to know what customers want. They look at the market to find out. After knowing customer demand, managers decide what to produce and how much. They also choose where and when to produce. Then, they plan scheduling and equipment maintenance.
The second step is supply. Managers make strategic decisions about core capabilities and outsourcing. They choose which divisions to use and may outsource to other companies. Outsourcing helps create velocity, meaning quality and flexibility with lower costs.

Hitler alive in Myanmar, sign says.

Ellen Page stands alone on a street. She holds a sign with a message. The sign says "Hitler is alive." Myanmar is a Southeast Asian country. It is ruled by a bad group. They took power in 1962. In 2007, monks protested against the bad group. They wanted freedom. This is called the Saffron Revolution. Many people were hurt. The bad group attacked monasteries. Journalists were also hurt. A Japanese reporter was killed. The bad group says only 13 people died. But a soldier says many more died.

This is not new. Many governments try to stop people from protesting. Early Roman and Japanese leaders thought they were gods. Our current president talks to a leader of a strange group. There were protests in China and Rwanda. Many people died in these places. Hitler's time was also bad.

Duke Ellington's music is important in jazz because he played for a long time and created many great pieces. Ellington was good at writing music that showed each band member's skills. He also wrote music that let band members improvise. Ellington's music is different because he used sound and style to make each piece unique. He was good at making the band sound good together. An example is "Creole Love Call," where he used the voice like an instrument. He also did this in "Hot and Bothered" and "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)."

She felt like something was missing. This feeling started when she was 14 and it was still there at 17. She wanted someone, not a thing. But no boys interested her. She wondered why. She thought about it for years but had no good answer. She lived her life, always asking herself what was wrong.

Usually, her home was peaceful. Her parents were calm and they rarely argued. They only argued about her wanting to be independent. She was likeable and nice.

Today was not peaceful. She heard a scream from the kitchen. She ran in and saw her mother in pain. Her mother said, "Ouch. I need the hospital." She carried her mother to the car and drove to the hospital.

At the hospital, she smelled disinfectant and sickness. But she was too busy helping her mother. Doctors looked at her mother. She waited, worried.

Her mother fell from a step stool. She wanted a vase from the highest cabinet.

This study shows that eating a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) is connected with a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. The Med diet has more plants, nuts, fish, and less meat and saturated fats. It also allows a small amount of alcohol.

Past studies said that the Med diet reduces heart disease and stroke risk. This study looked at 74,886 women who were part of the Nurses' Health Study for 20 years.

The women answered food questions six times, and their answers were checked. The study found that women who ate more like the Med diet had less heart disease and stroke. Women who ate more like the Med diet had a 29% lower risk of heart disease and stroke. This was true even after looking at other things like smoking or being overweight.

The study used a special math method to find the connection between diet and heart disease and stroke. The study shows that eating more like the Med diet helps prevent heart disease and stroke.

In 2007, the United States had a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs. The house prices fell. Big companies were in trouble. This crisis is still happening today. So, we must ask: How did this crisis start? How can we stop it? The crisis was caused by bad decisions by politicians. They made banks give loans to people who could not pay back. Banks sold these loans to other people. When people did not pay, the banks had no money. This caused many other problems in the economy. This crisis started in 1999. The President at that time wanted to stay in office. So, he changed the rules to make people happy. This led to the crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes wrote about this in the New York Times. He said that Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac would have problems during a tough economic time. Many things happened that caused the crisis. Some were new types of loans. These loans made the economy depend on the housing market. When the house prices fell, the banks had big problems. The five biggest banks in the USA had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007. This was about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, some banks were sold cheaply. Others were dismantled. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in mortgage debt. They were put under government control in 2008.

Story part, you call exposition.  It is not good.  Dr. Merlin yells at her computer when she has too much.  Too much information, not good.

You know the rule, "Show, don't tell."  Dr. Merlin sometimes forgets.  Too much exposition.

In movie, character tells another about big thing.  In story, author tells.  Not good.

Example: You read story.  Heroine met husband.  They married.  He died.  Not good if author takes two pages.

You need to show, not tell.  Show how they love each other.  Show how she feels.  Show how he feels.  Show why they are important.

You need to show meat, not just bone.  Sometimes, it is hard.  You want to rush.  You know things about character.  He was in Air Force.  Now, night manager.  Two times married.  No kids.  Likes fishing.  Dreams of gas station.  Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

You need to show, not tell.  Show why he likes Eggs Benedict.  Show what he thinks when he dreams.  Show how he feels at gas station.  Show why he is important.  Show how he changed heroine's life.  Show how they are connected.  Show why you should care about their story.

I watched two news programs from Columbus, Ohio. The first was NBC 4 on August 13, 2011. It showed a man, Shad Hostettler, who stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They showed his picture and said he was arrested. They spent about two minutes on this story.

The second story was about a young man, Travis Buyers, who was shot in Sharon Woods. He was injured and there were no arrests. They used the SWAT team to investigate. I thought this story was short. I have noticed that news about minorities is often short. If a white person is a victim of a crime, the news goes crazy. If a minority is a victim, they are lucky if they are mentioned.

Next, they talked about a gunshot hole in a helicopter. They said the shooter used a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information.

Then, they spoke about rain and thunderstorms on Saturday. They said the temperatures would be in the mid to low eighties for the weekend.

They also talked about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF store. The robber was a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie. They said he was about six feet tall and weighed 150 pounds. They spent a lot of time on this story, especially about how dark he was.

The next story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a convicted drug kingpin. He was sentenced to 300 months in prison for selling drugs in Ohio from Texas. They said he was Hispanic, but I did not think this was important to the story.

Brothers have a strong relationship. This includes love, pride, and anger. Brothers understand each other. They can see themselves in their brother. This bond is strong. When problems happen, this bond becomes clear. It is good or bad. When brothers look at each other, they see their true selves. The consequences of their actions show their true character. In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme. They have many feelings. These feelings are pride and anger. They go on a trip. In the end, one brother survives. The story shows how the protagonist, Doodle, feels. He has many emotions. His actions show these feelings. He feels proud. He wants to teach Doodle things. He thinks Doodle cannot do some activities. He is angry. He thinks about hurting Doodle. But Doodle smiles. This makes the protagonist feel better. He loves his brother. His love is strong.

The brain is complicated. It is like a special computer for information. As technology changed, so did brain metaphors. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to papyrus, then to a book, and now to a computer.
The brain starts with senses. Senses change physical things into signals. These signals are processed by the brain in two ways: top-down and bottom-up.
Top-down processing uses past decisions to speed up new ones. For example, when you see a black box, top-down processing helps you identify it quickly.
An attention filter decides which signals are important. The brain picks out important information, like your name in a noisy room.
The brain stores information. There are three types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Sensory memory keeps information for a short time. Working memory has an electrical loop to keep information for about 20 seconds.
Long-term memory stores information in protein structure. There are many models of how the brain organizes knowledge. The semantic network model has nodes for concepts and links for relatedness.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the future threat of both technology and capitalism. In Brave New World, people value community more than individuality. They are born to chase immediate happiness. The society is like a game. The World Controller controls the way they think and act.

The story shows signs of Marxist criticism. Huxley uses ideas like homogenization and reification. These ideas show he is against the way the economy is changing. Capitalism is shown as a harmful system.

The story uses Marxist ideas of false consciousness. This means people don't know the real relations between classes. They only care about their own gain. The lower classes, like Deltas and Gammas, are conditioned to love buying and consuming. They are not free to think differently. The upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, know the truth but don't change anything. The interactions between classes show the control of the upper class. It is like they are selling into an idea that supports capitalism.

People in Brave New World don't have real relationships. They are not deep. Maybe Huxley is saying that technology and capitalism take away people's free will. Love and deep emotions don't exist. People only care about physical appearances. The people are always happy to stay in their place in the society. This shows Marxist thought. They are tricked into thinking they are better by consuming and following the rules.

I have been at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Moving around campus can be hard. In my first year, I lived in East Halls, the furthest dorm from the center. Walking to Willard building took twenty-five minutes, especially with bad weather. The school used to have empty land where East Halls are now. Now, it is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As the campus grows, moving around gets harder. What is the best way to fix this? Bicycles. But, the campus needs to be good for bikes too.

I talked to a friend who rode a bike after a long break. He said, “Bikes are great. They are the best way to go.” Riding a bike is good for your health and easy for travel. A bowl of oatmeal and pedaling can take you thirty miles. I live off campus, as far as some dorms. The best thing I did this year was buy a bike. It takes five minutes to ride to Thomas building, where I have class. Walking would take thirty to forty minutes. That is two and a half hours each week. Without a bike, walking would be my only way to get around.
